    {
      "text": "A 23-year-old male patient visits you reporting a nasal discharge that appears like the image shown on a handkerchief. Which of the following characteristics aids in identifying the presence of CSF rhinorrhoea in this patient?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Halo sign"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Handkerchief sign"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Schwartz sign"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Phelps sign"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 0,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer A- <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"95af91681416927771887742113c38\">Halo</span> sign</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>The <strong>Halo sign</strong> is a classic characteristic used to identify <strong>CSF rhinorrhea</strong>. It is observed when <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"31c5d0e75f16927771938d8e2daa4c\">nasal</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9dd87431ba1692777186ecfb21d258\">discharge</span> on a handkerchief or tissue shows a <strong>central clear fluid surrounded by a ring of blood</strong>, creating a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"95af91681416927771887742113c38\">halo</span> pattern.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>This indicates the presence of <strong>cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)</strong> leaking from the <strong>subarachnoid space</strong> into the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"31c5d0e75f16927771938d8e2daa4c\">nasal</span> cavity, usually due to a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> in the skull base, often in the area around the <strong>ethmoid sinuses</strong>.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>CSF Rhinorrhea:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>\n\t<p><strong>CSF rhinorrhea</strong> occurs when <strong>cerebrospinal fluid</strong> leaks from the brain's <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0a5d82eeef169277719934b86fb07b\">subarachnoid</span> space into the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"31c5d0e75f16927771938d8e2daa4c\">nasal</span> cavity. This may be due to a <strong>skull base fracture</strong>, usually from trauma or surgery.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>The <strong>Halo sign</strong> is <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"552e9ef8811692777186997018b858\">diagnostic</span> when the fluid leaks from the nose and has a clear center with a blood ring around it, indicative of CSF.</p>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>\n\t<p>Symptoms often include <strong>clear <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"31c5d0e75f16927771938d8e2daa4c\">nasal</span> discharge</strong>, <strong>headaches</strong>, and <strong>a history of trauma</strong>.</p>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Incorrect Options:</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Handkerchief sign (Option B)</strong>: is incorrect because it is not a widely recognized term in clinical practice and does not specifically refer to the pattern seen in CSF rhinorrhea.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Schwartz sign (Option C)</strong>: is incorrect because it refers to a sign used in <strong>Biermer's disease (megaloblastic anemia)</strong> and is unrelated to CSF rhinorrhea.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Phelps sign (Option D)</strong>: is incorrect because it does not refer to any known clinical sign associated with CSF rhinorrhea.</p>",
